e tier.\n\n### Memory posture\nCurrent snapshot:\n- **9.7 GiB total**\n- **2.5 GiB used**\n- **3.3 GiB free**\n- **7.2 GiB available**\n- **Swap:** **8.0 GiB total**, essentially **unused**\n\n### Efficiency read\nRight now Phoenix looks **substantially healthier** than during the earlier pressure window:\n- RAM use is modest\n- available memory is strong\n- swap is basically untouched\n- channel health is clean\n\nThat means the earlier “swap-full” state appears to have cleared, or at least is not present in the current sample.\n\n### Efficiency verdict\n**Good efficiency / currently stable.**\nPhoenix is no longer showing the red-flag memory posture we saw before.\n\n---\n\n## Comparative assessment\n\n### Capacity\n- **Lucy wins on raw headroom**\n- 31 GiB RAM\n- no swap\n- more room for spikes\n\n### Cost-routing efficiency\n- **Phoenix wins on provider diversification**\n- mixes Codex, Groq, OpenRouter, Cerebras\n- better for keeping premium-model usage selective\n\n### Operational stability\n- **Both are healthy**\n- **Lucy** is the safer machine for sustained heavier work\n- **Phoenix** looks efficient now, but I’d still keep a light eye on it because we already observed one period of serious swap pressure earlier\n\n---\n\n## Treasury conclusions\n1. **Lucy should remain the primary heavy-lift node.**\n2. **Phoenix is currently efficient enough for active duty.**\n3. **Phoenix’s earlier memory event is worth remembering**, but it is **not** reflected in the current snapshot.\n4. **No immediate waste signal** is obvious from today’s health + memory + agent layout.\n5. Local auth usage files on Lucy showed **zero recorded error counts**, which is a good sign against retry-loop waste.\n\n---\n\n## One notable warning on Lucy\n`openclaw agents`/health output warned that:\n- `plugins.allow` is empty\n- non-bundled plugins may auto-load\n\nThat is more of a **security/control posture** note than an efficiency issue, but it’s worth tightening eventually.\n\n---\n\n